<p><big><font color="#800000"><big><b>Waves: Theory</b> </big></font></big><br>

<p><big><font color="#008040"><b>Introduction</b></font></big></p>
<p>The module simulates a "ripple tank" with the surface of the water
being the x-y plane. The user may place one or more monochromatic point sources
(which create circular waves), or monochromatic line sources (which create
waves with straight-line wavefronts, let's call them "linear waves") on the
water surface. The module shows the resultant disturbance, either in a static
form (a still picture) or as traveling waves.</p>

<p><big><font color="#008040"><b>Linear Wave (Line Source)</b></font></big></p>
<p>Each line source creates a linear wave of amplitude A, wavelength <font face=symbol>l</font>,
initial phase <font face=symbol>d</font>, and
angle of propagation <font face=symbol>q</font>.
The wave function for the disturbance at position (x,y) on the surface, at time
t, is given by the formula</p>

<div align="center"><center><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="90%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center><font face=symbol>y</font>(x,y,t) = Acos(k<sub>x</sub>x + k<sub>y</sub> 
    y - kvt +<font face=symbol>d</font>)</center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>(<a name="1">1</a>)</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center></center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../images/back.gif" alt="click to go to previous location" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></center></td>
  </tr>
</table></center></div>

<p>where k<sub>x</sub> = (2<font face=symbol>p</font>/<font face=symbol>l</font>)cos<font face=symbol>q</font>,
k<sub>y</sub> = (2<font face=symbol>p</font>/<font face=symbol>l</font>)sin<font face=symbol>q</font>,
and <img align=bottom src="images/image002.gif" width="142" height="32">. In Eq. (1) v is the wave speed. Fig. 1 below depicts a
linear wave of amplitude A, wavelength <font face=symbol>l</font>, initial phase zero, and angle of
propagation zero, i.e., the wave is propagating in the positive x-direction.</p>
<div align="center"><center><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><center><img src="images/image004.jpg" width="574" height="485"></center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><small>Figure 1 A linear wave traveling in the positive x-direction (towards the right).</small></td>
  </tr>
</table></center></div>
<p><a href=examples.html#waves-ex4>Example 4</a> simulates the waves from
a single line source. In it A, <font face=symbol>l</font>, <font face=symbol>d</font>, and <font face=symbol>q</font> are
varied. <a href=examples.html#waves-ex5>Example 5 </a>&nbsp;simulates the resultant wave for two identical linear waves
traveling in opposite directions. This is a <span style='color:red'>standing
wave</span> pattern. <a href=examples.html#waves-ex6>Example 6</a> simulates the
resultant wave for two identical linear waves traveling in different
directions. In which direction is the resultant wave traveling? <a href=examples.html#waves-ex7>Example 7</a> simulates the resultant wave for two waves
that are identical, except that they have slightly different wavelengths. This
causes <span style='color:red'>beats</span>. Can you identify the wave packets
as they travel by?</p>
<p><big><font color="#008040"><b>Circular Waves (Point Sources)</b></font></big></p>
<p>In this case the theory is more complex, because there is no such
thing as a truly "point" source. Therefore the module will simulate the waves
made by a small circular plunger of radius 'a' that is touching the water surface
and performing simple harmonic motion of angular frequency <font face=symbol>w</font> =
kv&nbsp; = (2<font face=symbol>p</font>/<font face=symbol>l</font>)v,
where v is the wave speed. Let F<sub>0</sub> be the maximum force per unit area
that the plunger exerts on the water. Let&nbsp;
T be the tension per unit length on the water surface, and let the
position of the point source be (x<sub>0</sub>, y<sub>0</sub>). The wave
function for the disturbance at the position (x,y) on the surface, at time t,
is given by the formula </p>
<div align="center"><center><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="90%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center><font face=symbol>y</font>(x,y,t) = B(x,y)cos(kvt - </span><font face=symbol>d</font>) + C(x,y)sin(kvt - <font face=symbol>d</font>)</center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>(<a name="2">2</a>)</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center></center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../images/back.gif" alt="click to go to previous location" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></center></td>
  </tr>
</table></center></div>
<p>where</p>
<div align="center"><center><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="90%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center><img width=332 height=93 src="images/image006.gif"></center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>(<a name="3">3</a>)</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center>&nbsp;</center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>&nbsp;</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center><img width=179 height=44 src="images/image008.gif"></center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>(<a name="4">4</a>)</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center>&nbsp;</center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>&nbsp;</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center><img width=76 height=42 src="images/image010.gif"></center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>(<a name="5">5</a>)</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center>&nbsp;</center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>&nbsp;</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center><img width=182 height=34 src="images/image012.gif"></center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center>(<a name="6">6</a>)</center></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%" class=tablemain><center></center></td>
    <td width="20%" class=tablemain><center><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../images/back.gif" alt="click to go to previous location" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></center></td>
  </tr>
</table></center></div>
<p>and <font face=symbol>b</font> = ka. Here J<sub>0</sub>(x) and J<sub>1</sub>(x) are Bessel functions of the
first kind of orders zero and one, respectively. N<sub>0</sub>(x) and N<sub>1</sub>(x)
are Bessel functions of the second kind (Neumann functions) of orders zero and
one, respectively. WebTOP uses Eqs. (2) through (5) to do its circular wave
calculations. In order to simulate a point source, it takes 'a' to be an
extremely small number. The user can vary the following parameters: A, <font face=symbol>l</font>, <font face=symbol>d</font>, x<sub>0</sub>,
and y<sub>0</sub>.</p>

<p>Fig. 2 below shows one circular wave from WebTOP:</p>

