  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><small>Figure 2 A circular wave due to a "point source" at the origin. The source itself is not pictured.</small></td>
  </tr>
</table></center></div>
<p><a href=examples.html#waves-ex1>Example 1</a> simulates the waves from
a single point source. In it A, <font face=symbol>l</font>,
<font face=symbol>d</font>, x<sub>0
</sub>and y<sub>0</sub> are varied. <a href=examples.html#waves-ex2>Example 2</a>
simulates the resultant wave when two identical, in-phase point sources are
separated by two, three, and four wavelengths. <a href=examples.html#waves-ex3>Example 3</a> simulates the resultant wave when three identical, in-phase point
sources are separated by two wavelengths</p>

